The sea was looked upon as a natural barrier, that ought not to be crossed. Ci. Hor. Od. 1, 3, 21-63 Ov. Met. 1, 94-6. Navigation and commerce were held in low esteem. ln their descriptions of the Golden Age the poets never fail to mention that there were no ships. Even Cicero thought commerce dishonorable unless its earnings were in· vested in estates; and then, as soon as possible, one must withdraw from it.
